</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="10" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="9.[840,1479,1344,1645]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
Distribution. Endemic to the province of KwaZulu-Natal in South Africa; occasional on grassland, scrub, and forest edges, on sandy soil, 
<quantity box="[949,1060,1399,1421]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.75" metricValueMax="13.0" metricValueMin="0.5" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" unit="m" value="675.0" valueMax="1300.0" valueMin="50.0">50–1300 m</quantity>
elevation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="10" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[840,1479,1344,1645]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<taxonomicName box="[864,1010,1427,1449]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="umtuma">
<emphasis box="[864,1010,1427,1449]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Solanum umtuma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is sympatric with and closely related [
<bibRefCitation author="Vorontsova MS &amp; Stern SS &amp; Bohs L &amp; Knapp S" box="[1391,1418,1428,1450]" journalOrPublisher="Bot J Linn Soc" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" refId="ref11249" refString="38. Vorontsova MS, Stern SS, Bohs L, Knapp S (2013) African spiny Solanum (subgenus Leptostemonum, Solanaceae): a thorny phylogenetic tangle. Bot J Linn Soc, in press." title="African spiny Solanum (subgenus Leptostemonum, Solanaceae): a thorny phylogenetic tangle" type="book" year="2013">38</bibRefCitation>
] to 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="linnaeanum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">S. linnaeanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[949,1124,1455,1476]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="linnaeanum">
<emphasis box="[949,1124,1455,1476]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Solanum linnaeanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has distinctive deeply incised leaves with rounded lobes (see 
<figureCitation box="[1105,1181,1483,1505]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="4.[155,220,172,191]" captionTargetBox="[160,1391,167,1911]" captionTargetId="figure-0@3.[155,1397,162,1916]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figure 1. Representative flower and fruit morphology of eggplant and its wild relatives. A. Solanum campylacanthum inflorescences (Kenya - Vorontsova et al. 157); B. Solanum incanum immature fruit (Kenya – Vorontsova et al. 203); C. Solanum insanum fruit cross-section (China – Wang et al. 2047); D. Solanum insanum inflorescence with several hermaphrodite flowers (China – Wang et al. 2039); E. Solanum linnaeanum with yellow mature and mottled green immature fruit, note highly dissected leaves (Spain - Knapp IM-10096); F. Solanum melongena flower with duplicated parts (China – Wang et al. 2042). Photographs: A, B taken M.S. Vorontsova; C, D, E, F taken by S. Knapp. doi:10.1371/journal.pone.0057039.g001" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6338574" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6338574/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Fig. 1E</figureCitation>
) while 
<taxonomicName box="[1269,1366,1483,1505]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="umtuma">
<emphasis box="[1269,1366,1483,1505]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">S. umtuma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has more shallowly lobed leaves with acute lobes although some specimens have been seen with rounded lobes. The flowers of 
<taxonomicName box="[1348,1439,1539,1560]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="umtuma">
<emphasis box="[1348,1439,1539,1560]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">S. umtuma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are usually pale lilac or white, while those of 
<taxonomicName box="[1245,1364,1566,1588]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="linnaeanum">
<emphasis box="[1245,1364,1566,1588]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">S. linnaeanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are purple. 
<taxonomicName box="[840,1012,1594,1616]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cerasiferum">
<emphasis box="[840,1012,1594,1616]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Solanum cerasiferum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also similar, but has less prickly calyces and deltate, rather than leafy, calyx lobes.
</paragraph>
